<H3> <TI>   Foreign Groups Denounce U.S. `Hostile' Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Groups Denounce U.S. `Hostile' Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2204104594 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1029 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2204104594 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 22 (KCNA) -- Foreign public circles 
denounce the U.S. hostile policy toward the DPRK and express 
support and solidarity for the Korean people's struggle of 
justice. 
  The chairman of the Central Committee of the National Union 
of Democratic Youth of Nepal in his speech at a mass rally in 
Katmandu on April 8 condemned the U.S. hostile policy toward the 
DPRK. 
  The ralliers adopted a letter of protest to U.S. President 
Bill Clinton and marched toward the U.S. Embassy shouting 
slogans with the placards "U.S. Imperialists, Promptly Stop 
Campaign Against North Korea Over Nuclear Issue" and "U.S. 
Imperialists, Quit Korean Peninsula." They handed the letter 
signed by 100 political and public figures to the U.S. Embassy. 
The letter demanded that the United States pull all its troops 
and nuclear weapons out of South Korea and give up the projected 
"sanctions" against the DPRK. 
  At a solidarity meeting held in Cuba earlier, the U.S. 
campaign against the DPRK was denounced and support and 
solidarity were expressed for the Korean people's just struggle. 
  A letter to the Korean people was adopted at the meeting. 
  The French Institute for the Development of International 
Relations in a communique April 6 expressed full support and 
solidarity for the Korean people's just stand toward the 
situation prevailing on the Korean peninsula. 
  Pierre Welo Ahondju Ewale, chairman of the Zaire-Korea 
Friendship Association, in a statement April 5 stressed that the 
United States must sincerely approach the unshakable attitude of 
the DPRK Government to find a peaceful, negotiated solution to 
the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula. 

</TEXT>

