<H3> <TI>   List of `Comfort Women' Found at U.S. Archives </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    List of `Comfort Women' Found at U.S. Archives </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2204045094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0425 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2204045094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 22 (KCNA) -- The fact-finding group 
on the forcible drafting of Koreans on April 18 discovered among 
documents kept at the U.S. National Archives lists of about 
10,000 Korean workers and women who were taken away by the 
Japanese imperialists for forced labour and as "comfort women 
for the army" during the Second World War, according to a KYODO 
report. 
  It was learned that the names of Korean workers and women 
drafted for forced labour and as "comfort women for the army" 
were in the lists of 180,000 soldiers of the former "Japanese 
Imperial Army" and civilian personnel who were taken prisoners 
of war by the allied forces in the Philippines. 
  The group plans to make public the lists soon. 

</TEXT>

