<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sam Rangsi Rebuts Charges in THE NATION </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sam Rangsi Rebuts Charges in THE NATION </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2204053994 Bangkok THE NATION in English 22 Apr 94 p A6 </F>
<F P=103> BK2204053994 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok THE NATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Letter to the editor from Finance Minister Sam Rangsi; date </F>
not given] 
  [Text] In Mr Michael Vickery's article entitled "Phnom Penh 
power plays" and published in your April 15, edition, the writer 
spoke of a "FUNCINPEC [National United Front for an Independent, 
Neutral, Peaceful, and Cooperative Cambodia] faction, probably 
centered on Sam Rangsi, which is lukewarm towards monarchy, 
especially of the Sihanouk variety." 
  Strangely, within the space of just a few words, Mr Vickery 
managed to make two basic errors of fact with reference to 
myself. First, it is completely mistaken to believe that I lead, 
or indeed am part of, any "faction" within the FUNCINPEC party. 
Second, to suggest that I -- together with a "faction" within 
FUNCINPEC -- am anything but completely devoted to the monarchy 
and, in particular, to the person of His Majesty the King is not 
only deeply insulting but also indicates a profound ignorance of 
my views and of Cambodian politics. 
  [Signed] Sam Rangsi 
  Ministry of State 
  Minister of Economics and Finance 
  Cambodia 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

