<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Policy Accord To `Spur' Tax Debate </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Policy Accord To `Spur' Tax Debate </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204093594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0928 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204093594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- A policy accord newly 
reached by the ruling coalition parties will spur discussions of 
a comprehensive tax reform to include income tax cuts and 
consumption and other indirect tax hikes, the head of a 
government tax panel said Friday [22 April]. 
  "The agreement is in the same direction with the panel's 
discussions... and confirmed that the tax reform will be decided 
in June and enacted at the Diet by the end of the year," Kan 
Kato, chairman of the Tax Commission, told reporters after a 
panel meeting. 
  The coalition reached the accord earlier in the day as a 
basis for forming a new cabinet, with Foreign Minister and 
Deputy Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata selected as the coalition's 
candidate to succeed Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  Under the accord, the coalition parties agreed on a plan to 
revamp the tax system while seeking "public understanding." The 
plan calls for revision or elimination of the 3 percent 
consumption tax while raising indirect taxes. 
  The chairman of the advisory panel to the prime minister 
interpreted the accord as calling for cutting direct taxes and 
raising indirect taxes. 
  Hosokawa asked the panel when it began its discussions 
earlier this month for income tax cuts and net tax increases to 
realize a balanced tax system for income, assets and consumption 
to cope with the coming aged society in the 21st century. 
  Panel members did not bring up the coalition accord at 
Friday's meeting, Kato said. 
  The panel will speed up its discussions by holding meetings 
on Tuesdays and Fridays from next week to compile a report with 
various options for the parties to decide in June, Kato said. 
  The meeting centered on administrative reform, with many 
panelists calling for further slimming of the government and its 
affiliated companies and institutions to win public support for 
net tax increases, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

