<H3> <TI>   Watanabe: No General Election Before Fall `95 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Watanabe: No General Election Before Fall `95 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204102594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1003 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204102594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- Former Foreign Minister 
Michio Watanabe of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) said 
Friday [22 April] that there will be no general election for the 
House of Representatives before the fall of 1995. Watanabe was 
speaking about the possible timing of a dissolution of the House 
of Representatives and subsequent election at a general meeting 
of Diet members belonging to his faction, the third largest 
within the main opposition party. 
  The election "will not be called for a certain period," the 
former deputy premier said, adding that "moves toward the 
general balloting will surface after the fall of next year." 
  The veteran conservative politician was apparently referring 
to the likelihood that a new government under Tsutomu Hata would 
press ahead with Hata's proposal to contest the next general 
vote under a new election system that combines single-seat 
constituencies and proportional representation. 
  Heads of coalition parties on Friday picked Foreign Minister 
Hata, who is head of the coalition's core party Shinseito [Japan 
Renewal Party], as its candidate for the premiership. Hata, 58, 
is almost certain to win the two elections to be held Monday in 
plenary sessions of the House of Representatives and the House 
of Councillors due to the coalition's majority. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

