<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa said Friday [22 April] he did not personally have a 
hand in a failure to report some 29 million yen of his personal 
income to tax authorities. "It is common for legislators to 
have their offices handle accounting and raising of funds, 
including their personal funds," Hosokawa said. 
  Hosokawa's chief political secretary, Namio Yatsuka, told a 
news conference earlier in the day that the prime minister did 
not disclose the 29 million yen income from stock and bond 
investment during a 10-year period from 1981. [passage omitted] 

