<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Food Imports Rise to Record High in 1993 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Food Imports Rise to Record High in 1993 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004105994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1040 GMT 20 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2004105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 20 KYODO -- Japan's food imports 
expanded 5.5 percent in 1993 to a record high 40,158.40 million 
dollars, going above the 40 billion dollar level for the first 
time, a governmental trade body said Wednesday [20 April]. The 
Japan External Trade Organization (Jetro) said the record high 
imports stemmed mainly from increases in fresh vegetables, beef, 
fish and rice. 
  Imports of fresh vegetables, which suffered a poor crop as a 
result of a cool and rainy summer last year, posted a 15.4 
percent climb, and those of beef rose 18.2 percent, supported by 
a reduction in custom duties and the yen's sharp rise, Jetro 
said. 
  An 11.1 percent increase in fish, which has the largest 
share 
of total imports, also contributed much to the record high, it 
said. 
  Imports of rice, which began as an emergency measure 
following a shortage of domestic rice in the wake of last year's 
unseasonable summer, totaled 107,900 tons worth 42.18 million 
dollars. 
  Orange imports rose a tiny 2.8 percent, discouraged by lower 
prices of domestic "mikan" mandarin oranges, while imports of 
orange juice plunged 25.9 percent in a reactionary move against 
last year's surge after liberalization of the farm product. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

