<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Interpretation of Talks Said Different </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Interpretation of Talks Said Different </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204131694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1306 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204131694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- Japan and the United 
States have fundamentally different interpretations of the 
overall goal of the so-called "framework" trade talks, a senior 
Trade Ministry official said Friday. 
  The perception gap emerged during the latest meeting between 
Japanese Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata and U.S. Trade 
Representative Mickey Kantor in Marrakech, Morocco, said the 
official at the Ministry of International Trade and Industry 
(MITI), who declined to be named. 
  The MITI official was referring to "basic objectives" 
mentioned in the joint statement on the Japan-U.S. framework, 
which was issued after the summit meeting between then Japanese 
Prime Minister Kiichi Miyazawa and U.S. President Clinton in 
Tokyo in July last year. 
  "The U.S. interpretation was found to be fundamentally 
different from Japan's understanding," said the official, who 
attended the Hata-Kantor meeting on April 15 in Morocco. 
  But the official did not explain the difference. He also 
refrained from specifying which part of the joint statement was 
discussed during the Marrakech meeting. 
  The Hata-Kantor meeting fell short of setting a specific 
time 
for resumption of the stalled framework talks. 
  The MITI official said that Kantor requested Tokyo to give a 
"satisfactory" answer to U.S. proposals made during the 
Marrakech meeting on three areas -- macroeconomic areas, 
objective criteria and overall goal. But the official declined 
to reveal details of the proposals. 
  The MITI official said the U.S. proposals on the three areas 
were "far from" acceptable for Tokyo. He said Tokyo will make a 
reply to these proposals by sending an official to Washington 
probably after the Golden Week holiday season ending on May 8. 
  The Japanese understanding is that Washington is prepared to 
reopen the framework talks through informal channels, only when 
the Japanese answer is found "satisfactory," the MITI official 
said. 
  During the Hata-Kantor meeting, Kantor sounded "softer" on 
the issue of numerical targets, the idea of which Hata flatly 
dismissed at the outset of the meeting, the MITI official said. 
But the official did not elaborate, only saying Kantor did not 
show any response. 
  Asked if the Japan-U.S. trade ties have worsened after the 
Hata-Kantor meeting compared with the situation immediately 
after the February 11 breakdown of the summit, the MITI official 
said it is difficult to judge. Tokyo could avoid discussing the 
conceptual gap over the "basic objectives," if it focuses on 
sector-by-sector discussion, the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-6639 </DOCNO>
