<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Rejects Joining Naval Blockade of DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tokyo Rejects Joining Naval Blockade of DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104025994 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 21 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2104025994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 21 April Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] In connection with the issue of how to deal with the 
DPRK's suspected development of nuclear weapons, which is one of 
the focal issues in the ruling coalition parties' ongoing policy 
coordination meeting, a government source said on the morning of 
20 April that if a naval blockade is implemented as part of 
economic sanctions by the UN Security Council, Japan "will not 
participate in sanctions premised on the use of force." He thus 
indicated that Japan will not participate in such a naval 
blockade. 
  While a blockade is meant to ensure the effectiveness of 
economic sanctions, and no use of force is involved in the 
objective and mission of such an action, "corresponding 
measures" are permitted under "certain conditions"--for 
instance, if the other party resorts to armed resistance. 

</TEXT>

