<H3> <TI>   New Zealand Premier Urges PRC Role in DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Zealand Premier Urges PRC Role in DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2104033494 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 21 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2104033494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 21 April Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] In an interview with a NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN reporter 
in Tokyo on 20 April, New Zealand Deputy Prime Minister Don 
McKinnon, who is on a visit to Japan, said, "We must keep in 
mind that China is not as concerned over the issue of North 
Korea's suspected development of nuclear weapons as are other 
nations." In the interview, he also said he was doubtful about 
how far China would go in taking concerted steps with Japan, the 
United States, and South Korea to resolve the issue. 
  In late March, the UN Security Council issued a presidential 
statement calling on North Korea to accept international 
inspections of its nuclear facilities. Commenting on the 
opinion that China took the initiative in issuing the 
presidential statement, the New Zealand deputy prime minister 
denied that China took any initiative, saying, "Other nations 
decided to issue that presidential statement out of 
consideration for China." In calling China the "player who 
holds the key," he stressed the need to continue the efforts to 
urge China to get involved in the issue. 

</TEXT>

