<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chief Cabinet Secretary Likely From Shinseito </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chief Cabinet Secretary Likely From Shinseito </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2004140794 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 20 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2004140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 19 April, a Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] 
leader commented on the appointment of chief cabinet secretary, 
a focal point in the selection of members of the "new 
administration of Tsutomu Hata." He indicated his basic 
intention to appoint a Shinseito member as chief cabinet 
secretary, saying: "The relationship between chief cabinet 
secretary (and prime minister) is like being bound by a common 
fate. We hope that a person who is on friendly terms with the 
new prime minister will be named as chief cabinet secretary." 
In concrete terms, it is believed that he made the remarks 
while keeping in mind Hajime Funada, former director general of 
the Economic Planning Agency, and other Shinseito members. In 
this connection, a Komeito leader said on the same day: "It is 
appropriate to appoint a Shinseito member as the chief cabinet 
secretary." He indicated that if the number of cabinet posts 
occupied by Shinseito members increases, it is better to adjust 
the allocation of cabinet posts rather than that of the chief 
cabinet secretary. A Democratic Socialist Party leader agreed 
with them. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

