<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 19 KYODO -- The government-backed 
Japan National Oil Corp. said Tuesday [19 April] it has reached 
basic agreement to conduct geological surveys for oil and 
natural gas in the Republic of Kazakhstan of the former Soviet 
Union. 
  The corporation and Kazakhstan authorities have been 
conducting negotiations since May 1993 on possible surveys in 
the republic, which is believed to be rich in oil and natural 
gas resources, officials said. They said the three-year 
surveys, costing 5.3 billion yen, will cover a 
10,000-square-kilometer land area northwest of the Aral Sea. 

