<H3> <TI>   ExIm Bank Extends Credit Lines to Baltic States </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ExIm Bank Extends Credit Lines to Baltic States </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1904043494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0349 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1904043494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 19 KYODO -- The Export-Import [ExIm] 
Bank of Japan announced Tuesday [19 April] the signing of 
agreements to establish untied credit lines equivalent to up to 
100 million dollars to the Baltic countries to help support 
infrastructure projects. The loans consist of 30 million 
dollars each to Estonia and Latvia and 40 million dollars to 
Lithuania, the governmental bank said. 
  The bank said the loans will be provided in collaboration 
with the European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) 
under a government loan program for developing countries mapped 
out last June. 
  The bank extended a total of 100 million dollars to the 
Baltic states last year in co-financing with the World Bank. 

</TEXT>

