<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Spokesman on Meeting With DPRK Officials </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    IAEA Spokesman on Meeting With DPRK Officials </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2204004294 Seoul HANGUK ILBO in Korean 22 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> SK2204004294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul HANGUK ILBO </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Han Ki-pong from Paris] </F>
  [Text] David Kyd, spokesman for the International Atomic 
Energy Agency [IAEA], said on 21 April that the IAEA is now 
meeting with high-level officials of the North Korean mission in 
Vienna to concretely discuss the timing and method of additional 
inspection of the North Korean nuclear facilities. 
  Spokesman Kyd said that "it is highly possible that North 
Korea will accept additional inspections of its nuclear 
facilities before the end of April, at the earliest, as wished 
by the IAEA," and added that "in preparation for the smooth 
progress of discussions with North Korea, the IAEA is ready to 
send its inspection team to Pyongyang within next week." 
  On 20 April, North Korea sent a message to the IAEA 
proposing 
that IAEA inspectors witness the upcoming change of fuel bars at 
its 5-megawatt nuclear reactor in Yongbyon. 
  An IAEA source also said that "in the message North Korea 
asked the IAEA to witness the upcoming change of fuel bars at 
its nuclear reactor," and that "this is the first concrete 
reaction from North Korea to the international community's 
request for additional nuclear inspection." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

