<H3> <TI>   Yi Yong-tok Designated New Premier </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yi Yong-tok Designated New Premier </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2204084294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0836 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2204084294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 22 (YONHAP) -- President Kim Yong-sam 
accepted the resignation tendered by Prime Minister Yi Hoe-chang 
Friday and named Yi Yong-tok, deputy prime minister and National 
Unification minister, to succeed Yi Hoe-chang as new prime 
minister. 
  President Kim told his secretaries to submit to the 
National Assembly on Saturday a bill asking for parliamentary 
endorsement of his appointment of Yi Yong-tok as new prime 
minister. 
  Chongwadae [presidential office] spokesman Chu Ton-sik said 
in an announcement soon after Yi Hoe-chang's weekly Chongwadae 
[meeting] reporting that "Prime Minister Yi tendered his 
resignation as prime minister at 5 p.m. and President Kim 
accepted it promptly." 
  President Kim met Prime Minister Yi at Chongwadae for about 
40 minutes beginning 4 p.m., during which the president was 
learned to have reproached Yi in connection with his recent 
behavior. 
  A source said that Prime Minister Yi did not express his 
intent of resignation during his Chongwadae meeting with the 
president. 
  But, on return to his office in the integrated government 
building, Yi tendered his resignation through Government 
Administration Minister Hwang Yong-ha, the source said. 
  The acceptance by President Kim of Yi's resignation is taken 
as the revelation of the president's determination to firm up 
the discipline of the cabinet under the presidential system. 
  The president is expected to appoint a new deputy prime 
minister and national unification minister soon after the 
parliament endorsed the choice of Yi Yong-tok as new prime 
minister. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

