<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parties Show Mixed Reactions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parties Show Mixed Reactions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2204115494 Seoul YONHAP in English 1145 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2204115494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 22 (YONHAP) -- Political parties showed 
mixed reactions on the resignation Friday of Prime Minister Yi 
Hoe- chang. 
  The ruling Democratic Liberal Party said it was 
inconsiderate 
of outgoing Prime Minister Yi to resign without wisely striding 
over a mountain of important state affairs. 
  "We regret it that Prime Minister Yi, whom we expected to 
wisely surmount many important state affairs, tendered 
resignation all of a sudden," party spokesman Ha Sun-pong said. 
  "We believe Prime Minister-designate Yi Yong-tok, with his 
high virtues and rich experiences, would wisely overcome today's 
difficulties to make the people feel easier." 
  The opposition Democratic Party said the party regrets Prime 
Minister Yi's resignation which it said was caused by "reckless 
checks" by those in power. 
  "The people expected much from Prime Minister Yi. But, he 
couldn't unfold his policy and had to step down due to reckless 
checks," party spokesman Pak Chi-won said. 
  "We fear if Yi Yong-tok's appointment as prime minister 
won't 
turn the administration more conservative," he said. 
  The United People's Party said the party was shocked at 
Prime 
Minister Yi Hoe-chang having resigned for the reason that he 
couldn't fulfill the duty given him under the Constitution. 

</TEXT>

