<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reporter Punished for Protection Law Violation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reporter Punished for Protection Law Violation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2204101294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0808 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2204101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 22 (YONHAP) -- The Seoul high court on 
Friday handed down two years in jail with a three-year stay of 
execution to Shinohara Masato, the Seoul correspondent of 
Japan's Fuji Television convicted of violating the military 
secret protection law. 
  Shinohara, 41, was sentenced earlier to a two-year prison 
term in a lower court and appealed his case to the high court. 
  In his decision, Judge Min Su-myong said, "the defendant 
rightly deserves the punishment as he violated this country's 
military secret protection law when he spied to obtain military 
secrets for three years and gave them to military attaches at 
the Japanese Embassy in Seoul." 
  The court believes, however, that he was interested in 
military secrets more as a journalist and analyst for his 
articles than as a spy, the judge said. 
  Moreover, this incident does not appear to have had a 
decisive adverse effect on the country's security, the judge 
said. Besides, he noted that Shinohara confessed before 
authorities began questioning him. 
  Considering all the extenuating circumstances, the judge 
said 
he decided to give Shinohara a lenient sentence. 
  Shinohara was indicted last July on charges of receiving 27 
military secrets from former Major Ko Yong-chol, who was working 
in the intelligence headquarters of the Defense Ministry, 
turning them over to Japanese military attaches on a regular 
basis between 1989 and 1990. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

