<H3> <TI>   Radio Questions Thailand's Sincerity </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio Questions Thailand's Sincerity </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2404122594 Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2404122594 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh National Radio of Cambodia Network 
in Cambodian 1300 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Cambodian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Station commentary: "Is It an Appeal or a Threat?"] </F>
  [Text] According to AFP, Thailand has recently proposed a 
meeting of ASEAN representatives in Thailand next week to 
discuss a conflict with Cambodia which is apparently becoming 
ceaselessly more and more serious and which seems to be slipping 
toward the edge of a ravine. Thai Foreign Minister Prasong 
Sunsiri said Thailand will (?listen to) the ASEAN 
representatives' opinions on the (?dispute) at a meeting, which 
will prepare for an ASEAN ministerial meeting in (?June), to be 
held in Bangkok next week. 
  Moreover, a report from Bangkok said Prasong on 18 April 
appealed to diverse countries or outsiders to stop supplying 
armaments and ammunition to Cambodia, saying the military aid 
would further inflame the conflict between the Phnom Penh 
government and Khmer Rouge rebels. The Thai foreign minister 
also told reporters in Bangkok that the aid was not (?an 
approach) to solving the problem. He added that various 
countries and outsiders appear to be bringing more violence to 
Cambodia on top of the existing conflict. 
  It is wondered whether Pasong Sunsiri's [words indistinct] 
statement contradicts the accusation by the Royal Government of 
Cambodia [RGC] about Thailand's recent support for the Khmer 
Rouge -- support that is contrary to Thailand's pledge made 
during Chuan Likphai's visit to Cambodia -- and that Thailand 
supports the Cambodian government, not the Khmer Rouge. 
  According to the 19 April issue of Thailand's THE NATION, 
Thai Army Chief General Wimon Wongwanit has issued an indignant 
threat to Cambodian leaders, warning them that Thailand can no 
longer maintain a good relationship [words indistinct], 
referring to Phnom Penh's accusing Thailand of helping Khmer 
Rouge leaders. 
  Wimon added that between human beings, true friendship is 
very important, and so it is with international relations. 
Without sincerity, there can be no friendship. He further said 
that [word indistinct] without Thailand as a true friend, 
Cambodia would certainly be in trouble. 
  Observers wonder why, since the Cambodian Government 
occupied 
the Khmer Rouge's important bases along the border, Thailand has 
never expressed support for the occupation or denounced the 
Khmer Rouge. It has only done things, such as the recent 
repatriation of 25,000 Cambodian refugees in violation of human 
rights, that appear to be opposed to victories by the RGC and 
opposed to international organizations. Analysts are anxious 
about the conflict, which is becoming more and more serious. 
  As for the Kingdom of Cambodia, it has always wanted peace 
and friendship. It is also grateful to its friends for their 
understanding. We wholeheartedly welcome (?Thai) friends, but 
not those having a vested interest. The Cambodian people have 
never practiced the policy of catching a fish with two hands. 

</TEXT>

