<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   State Budget Increases Investment in Some Sectors </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    State Budget Increases Investment in Some Sectors </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2304125194 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1011 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2304125194 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 23 (KCNA) -- The Democratic 
People's Republic of Korea is giving definite precedence to the 
coal industry, the power industry and rail transport which must 
advance ahead of the other sectors of the national economy. 
  The state budget for this year envisages a rise of 3 percent 
above last year in the investments in these sectors. 
  In the coal industry, the coal mines will concentrate on 
securing more reserve coal deposits and cutting faces by 
accelerating tunnelling and pit construction and on modernizing 
coal-cutting equipment. 
  In the power industry, the construction of large 
hydroelectric power stations and thermal power plants currently 
under way will be accelerated vigorously and many more minor 
power stations be built in all parts of the country. 
  In rail transport, the existing rails will be replaced by 
heavy-duty rails at an accelerated pace on the trunk lines 
including the Pyongyang-Chongjin line, more sections be switched 
over to electric traction and the modernisation of transport 
means be hastened to increase the railway transport capacity. 
  The investment will be up in the metal industry 2.6 percent 
on last year and the production of irons and steels will be 
placed on a reinforced foundation. 
  Last year the investment in the preferential sectors of the 
national economy went up 3.5 percent above the preceding year to 
considerably increase the capacity of coal and ore production. 
  Power production and railway transport capacity has been 
largely boosted with efforts concentrated on the construction of 
power stations and the strengthening of the material and 
technological foundations of railways. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

