<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Suharto, Iraqi Envoy Discuss UN Sanction Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Suharto, Iraqi Envoy Discuss UN Sanction Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2204125494 Baghdad Republic of Iraq Radio Network in 
Arabic 1030 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2204125494 </F>
<F P=104>  Baghdad Republic of Iraq Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Jakarta today, Indonesian President Suharto 
received a National Assembly delegation led by Speaker Sa'di 
Mahdi Salih, President Saddam Husayn's envoy. Suharto welcomed 
them to Indonesia and said he hoped their contacts with 
Indonesian parliamentarians would further boost bilateral ties. 
The president noted that during a visit earlier in the week to 
Indonesia by Muhammad Sa'id al-Sahhaf, the foreign minister 
discussed with him recent developments in the UN Security 
Council [with regard to Iraq's demand that the sanctions be 
lifted]. Suharto told Salih that Indonesia takes a keen 
interest in the matter and will pursue it in its capacity as the 
current president of the Nonaligned Movement through its 
coordination bureau in Jakarta and liaison office in New York. 
Indonesia also plans to contact the movement's nations who are 
not permanent Security Council members. In case no suitable 
solution is worked out to end the hardships the Iraqis are 
experiencing from the sanctions, Indonesia, Suharto added, will 
explore other avenues. His country also stands ready to extend 
humanitarian assistance to the Iraqi people, particularly 
medicines. 
  Sa'di Mahdi Salih thanked the Indonesian president for his 
time and for the positive approach of the Indonesian leadership 
and people to Iraq. 

</TEXT>

