<F P=100> Indonesia </F>
<H3> <TI>   MP Calls PRC Reaction to Medan Riots `Excessive' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    MP Calls PRC Reaction to Medan Riots `Excessive' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2404085594 Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network in 
Indonesian 0000 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2404085594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jakarta Radio Republik Indonesia Network </F>
<F P=105>  Indonesian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Parliamentary News Roundup"] </F>
  [Excerpt] [Passage omitted] [Correspondent] Theo 
Sambuaga, vice chairman of House Commission I [in charge of 
foreign affairs, defense, security, and information] considers 
the Chinese Government's statement on the labor case in Medan 
too excessive. According to Sambuaga, from the United 
Development Faction, the Chinese Government's statement was 
improper in the context of friendly relations between the two 
countries. 
  [Sambuaga] The statement can affect good relations between 
the two countries because it can be interpreted as an act of 
interference in Indonesia's internal affairs. It is important 
that such an official statement be made cautiously because it 
may incite or contribute to undesirable racial conflicts in 
Indonesia. Certainly, the Chinese Government and other 
governments know that Indonesia has consistently handled various 
problems through swift legal approaches and has never 
discriminated against its citizens on the basis of ethnicity, 
religion, or least of all race. The government has consistently 
upheld it's principles in resolving all problems, not just what 
happened in Medan with all its excesses. There have been no 
problems. What happened in Medan stemmed from irresponsible 
acts, and legal action will definitely be taken against the 
culprits. 
  [Correspondent] In this regard, Theo Sambuaga urged the 
Department of Foreign Affairs to brief the Chinese ambassador on 
the incident so the Chinese Government will not make a wrong 
judgment of the events in Indonesia. 

</TEXT>

