<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official on Soviet-DPRK Pact Interpretations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official on Soviet-DPRK Pact Interpretations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2304003494 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2200 GMT 22 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2304003494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [YONHAP report from Moscow] </F>
  [Text] Russia is not obligated to promptly assist North 
Korea pursuant to its treaty of military alliance with North 
Korea even if a military dispute occurs on the Korean peninsula, 
a senior Russian Government official said. 
  Valentin Moiseyev, chief of the Korean division of the 
Foreign Ministry's First Asian Department, interviewed by 
ITAR-TASS today, said this adding that Russia has already 
modified the interpretation of the clause on automatic military 
intervention, which is the key clause of the DPRK-Soviet Treaty 
on Friendship, Cooperation, and Mutual Assistance signed in 1961. 
  He explained that Russia conveyed its position on the 
modification of the automatic military intervention clause to 
Pyongyang about a year ago through a diplomatic channel. 
  Moiseyev noted that although Russia, which succeeded the 
Soviet Union, admits that the treaty is still valid, a different 
interpretation has to be made as to the automatic military 
intervention clause under the present circumstances. 

</TEXT>

