<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Major Units Ordered `To Stay on Full Alert' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Major Units Ordered `To Stay on Full Alert' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2304054994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0532 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2304054994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 23 (YONHAP) -- The Defense Ministry 
instructed commanders of major military units Saturday to stay 
on full alert for North Korean troop movements. 
  Over 50 commanding officers from the Army, Navy, Air Force 
and Joint Chiefs of Staff attended a meeting at the ministry 
held to analyze the latest developments in the North Korean 
nuclear impasse and Pyongyang's military movements. 
  The meeting, presided over by Defense Minister Yi Pyong-tae, 
concluded that North Korea has not showed any signs of forward 
movement but that the North's conventional troops still pose a 
threat of attack. 
  The commanders also decided that North Korea is unlikely to 
abandon its nuclear program despite South Korean-U.S. efforts at 
dialogue, leaving the issue clouded by uncertainty. 
  North Korean aggression cannot be ruled out if the matter is 
referred to the UN Security Council for sanctions, they said. 
  Yi instructed the military to support the government's 
policy 
on resolving the nuclear crisis through dialogue, while 
remaining on full alert to deter any attack and maintaining an 
early warning system in cooperation with the United States. 
  Yi asked the armed forces to prepare for the South 
Korean-U.S. joint military exercise "Team Spirit," scheduled to 
open in November unless the nuclear problem is sufficiently 
defused. 

</TEXT>

