<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   No U.S. Response on MOU Difference of Opinion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No U.S. Response on MOU Difference of Opinion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2304075894 Seoul KYONGHYANG SINMUN in Korean 23 April 94 p 
2 </F>

<F P=103> SK2304075894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KYONGHYANG SINMUN </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [YONHAP from Washington] </F>
  [Text] The ROK and U.S. Governments are having a 
difference of opinion over the export of the ROK defense 
industry, said officials of the two countries on 21 April. 
  According to ROK and U.S. sources, the ROK Government, via a 
diplomatic channel, has officially asked the United States to 
approve of the ROK's sale of military equipment to other 
countries, However, the United States has showed no reaction so 
far. 
  Under the Memorandum of Understanding [MOU] on the defense 
industry signed between the two governments, in principle, the 
ROK has to have U.S. approval in order to sell military 
equipment manufactured with U.S. technology to a third country. 
  Pointing out that the details of the MOU were eased in 1982 
and 1989 to pave the way for the ROK to more readily export 
military equipment, the sources said that the recent official 
request was based on this adjustment. 
  The U.S. Government was originally scheduled to respond to 
the ROK Government's request on sales in some 15 fields, 
including artillery of various types and armored personnel 
carriers, to Southeast Asia and Latin America by last February, 
but has yet failed to respond, added the sources. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

