<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ministry Denies Plans To Purchase U.S. Weapons </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ministry Denies Plans To Purchase U.S. Weapons </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2304082994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0817 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2304082994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 23 (YONHAP) -- The Defense Ministry has 
denied as "unfounded" the foreign press report that South Korea 
had decided to purchase a large amount of American-made 
sophisticated weapons. 
  A Ministry official said on Friday that there were no talks 
at all on the possible purchase of Apache helicopters, Patriot 
missiles and other high-tech weapons from the United States 
during the recent visit to Seoul by U.S. Defense Secretary 
William Perry. 
  THE WALL STREET JOURNAL of the United States reported that 
during Perry's visit to Seoul, South Korea agreed to buy a host 
of American-made high-tech weapons. 
  "Apart from Perry's visit, we had partially modified the 
Yulgok arms procurement program in a way that places a more 
emphasis on building up our anti-artillery and night-time battle 
ability," the official said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

