<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Provinces Agree To Buy More ROK Goods </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Provinces Agree To Buy More ROK Goods </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2504014394 Seoul YONHAP in English 0132 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2504014394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 25 (YONHAP) -- The South Korean and 
Chinese trade ministers agreed Monday that Chinese provincial 
governments should use more Korean steel, chemicals, foodstuffs 
and machinery. 
  The agreement came as Trade, Industry and Energy Minister 
Kim 
Chol-su met with visiting Chinese Minister of Internal Trade 
Zhang Haoruo for talks on promoting bilateral economic links. 
  Officials said Kim asked Zhang to open the Chinese market to 
official auto imports from South Korea. He also requested 
China's active interest in allowing South Korea's corporate 
entry into the distribution market since it is linked with 
bilateral trade expansion, officials said. 
  Zhang, in response, said South Korean companies should 
invest 
mainly in improving and building China's distribution network 
including warehouses and marine transport centers. 
  The two trade ministers decided that Seoul would send a 
government-private study team to China around June or July to 
look into the distribution market. 
  They agreed that their governments would fully support the 
planned construction of the Korea business center in Beijing and 
an oil refinery that South Korea's Yukong hopes to build in 
Liangchuan. 

</TEXT>

