<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to Prime Minister Resignation Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reaction to Prime Minister Resignation Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    DLP Opposes Yi Yong-tok Approval </H4>

<F P=102> SK2304000294 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2200 GMT 22 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2304000294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A dispute over the National Assembly's approval of 
the appointment of the acting prime minister is expected between 
the ruling and opposition parties. 
  The Democratic Liberal Party [DLP] will hold a high-ranking 
post-holders meeting today to confirm the position that the 
president's decision to accept the resignation of Prime Minister 
Yi Hoe-chang has no legal or political flaw as it was an 
exercise of the president's own sovereign power. 
  The DLP is expected to confirm the determination to 
consolidate the party's power to achieve the national goal of 
strengthening the country's competitiveness under closer party 
cooperation after the appointment of the new prime minister. 
  The Democratic Party [DP] will hold an emergency executives' 
meeting today to demand that the prime minister's rights be 
stipulated in the Constitution and finalize its position to 
oppose the approval of the appointment of new acting Prime 
Minister Yi Yong-tok by the National Assembly. 
  Fierce dispute between the ruling and opposition party is 
expected over the approval of the prime minister's appointment 
and over the National Assembly's investigation on the Sangmudae 
political fund case. 

</TEXT>

