Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Formation of Cabinet Delayed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Formation of Cabinet Delayed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504133094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1323 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504133094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- The formation of newly 
elected Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata's cabinet was delayed Monday 
[25 April] because the Social Democratic Party (SDP) reacted 
sharply to the abrupt establishment of a new 130-legislator 
parliamentary group in the House of Representatives that 
excludes the party. 
  An intracoalition standoff intensified a few hours after the 
Diet voted to sweep Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] leader Hata, 
58, to power as the replacement for Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa. 
  The new parliamentary caucus, named "Kaishin (Innovation)," 
comprises Shinseito, the Japan New Party, the Democratic 
Socialist Party (DSP), as well as two splinter groups that 
recently defected from the opposition Liberal Democratic Party 
-- the Liberal Party and Kaikaku no Kai. 
  By incorporating former Labor Minister Toshio Yamaguchi, the 
parliamentary strength of the new camp shot up to 130. 
Yamaguchi himself is an LDP rebel. The group's strength has 
already dwarfed the SDP's strength of 74. 
  Wataru Kubo, secretary general of the SDP, blasted the 
sudden 
attempt to alter the coalition's makeup for betraying the SDP, 
which was the largest contingent in the ruling coalition. 
  The SDP apparently perceives the sudden convergence of five 
political blocs as a move aimed at accomplishing a proposal by 
the Shinseito-led conservative mainstream to create a new 
unified party, political analysts said. 
  Shinseito Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa and his Komeito 
counterpart Yuichi Ichikawa originally proposed such a 
convergence to defeat the LDP in an upcoming general election 
under the newly legislated electoral system, which has 
introduced a mix of single-seat constituencies and proportional 
representation. 
  The leaders of the coalition were originally scheduled to 
begin talks on the formation of a second coalition at 4 P.M. 
[0700 GMT] but the SDP's rage apparently delayed the start of 
the consultations for more than four hours until SDP Chairman 
Tomiichi Murayama went to the premier's official residence at 
8:30 P.M. However, Murayama walked out of the meeting 18 
minutes later to discuss his party's response at the SDP 
Headquarters. 
  The move suddenly gathered momentum when DSP Chairman Keigo 
Ouchi told DSP legislators the coalition parties should initiate 
such a parliamentary group to create a "firm support base" for 
the Hata administration. The DSP leader was earlier one of the 
chief critics of such a move. 
  Kubo, the SDP's chief strategist, told reporters, however, 
"it is a universal rule to live by the etiquette based on mutual 
trust and obligations. It is outrageous for them to suddenly 
initiate this move on the very day of a cabinet formation 
despite the fact that the SDP has cooperated with other 
coalition partners in running the government until today," Kubo 
said. 
  Ouchi later told a news conference, "the reason why we have 
to establish the parliamentary group to back up the new prime 
minister is to facilitate the implementation of the nine-point 
policy platform agreed upon by the coalition parties." 
  The platform was created after two weeks of squabbles and 
standoffs since Hosokawa suddenly announced his resignation 
April 8. 
  Ouchi also said, "We need to consolidate the parliamentary 
base to support the prime minister and we put together parties 
that could quickly agree to the convergence as it is hard to 
enlist all the parties immediately into the new group." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

