<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Meets With Shinseito Legislators </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Meets With Shinseito Legislators </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504105794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1037 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504105794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- Tsutomu Hata was 
elected prime minister Monday [25 April] by Japan's bicameral 
Diet, as Japan faces such crucial issues as a trade row with the 
United States, tax reform and the suspected North Korean 
development of nuclear weapons. 
  Hata, 58, leader of Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], a core 
party in the coalition, became Japan's 51st premier and the 
sixth prime minister in five years, succeeding Morihiro 
Hosokawa, 56. [passage omitted] 
  Later in a meeting with Shinseito legislators, Hata appealed 
for greater allegiance, saying "Japan is facing difficult times 
domestically and internationally." He was apparently referring 
to the recession, trade tensions with the United States and the 
North Korean nuclear issue. "If Japan made a wrong policy 
choice, it would plunge into an abyss and historians (of the 
future) will look back and say there used to be a country named 
Japan," Hata warned. 
  He hinted, however, that he would not lead Japan to take a 
high profile role in U.N. peacekeeping efforts, saying, "I am 
not asserting that the Japanese should go abroad carrying 
bazookas on their shoulders." 
  LDP president Kono called on Hata to step up efforts for 
political reform to restore the credibility of Japanese politics. 
  "I want to see him work toward dispelling the people's 
distrust in politics," Kono told reporters. "I heard the ruling 
coalition say repeatedly that it should follow through on 
promised political reform in order to restore the credibility of 
politics," Kono said. 
  Former Foreign Minister Michio Watanabe of the LDP urged the 
governing coalition to live up to its vow to implement policies 
earlier agreed upon as a policy platform. "I want the Hata 
administration to carry out policies which were worked out by 
Shinseito," said Watanabe, who threatened in mid-April to leave 
the party in a bid to seek the premiership, hoping for backing 
from some of the ruling coalition. The leader of the LDP's 
third-largest faction said, "we will extend our support for (the 
Hata administration's) policies that could help our country, 
while withholding support for any policies that could not." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

