<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Reaction to Hata's Election Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Reaction to Hata's Election Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Ministers Urge Continuing Reform </H4>

<F P=102> OW2504041494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0409 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504041494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- Japan's exiting industrial 
and economic planning chiefs called Monday for the new 
government to carry on with deregulation and consumer-based 
reforms. 
  After a morning cabinet meeting in which Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa's cabinet resigned en masse, Hiroshi Kumagai, 
head of the Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI), 
said the survival of Japan's economy depends on further 
deregulation. 
  "Japan has taken only the first step in its deregulation 
efforts," Kumagai said. "The fire for reforms built up by Mr. 
Hosokawa should not be extinguished." 
  Manae Kubota, director general of the Economic Planning 
Agency (EPA), urged the new government, to be headed by outgoing 
Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata, to put priority on consumers. 
She said that while promoting deregulation and other reforms, 
the new government should focus on such issues as seeing that 
the benefits of the high yen are passed on to consumers and 
repeated that income tax cuts to stimulate the economy should 
precede an offsetting hike in such indirect levies as the 
consumption tax. 
  Political sources speculated that Kumagai will keep his post 
as MITI minister under Hata. Kubota said she had heard nothing 
of her own prospects. 
  On trade issues, Kumagai hinted at perplexity on new U.S. 
proposals to restart stalled bilateral "framework" talks, saying 
Washington's approach should be "a bit clearer." 
  Contents have not been disclosed of the U.S. proposal Hata 
received as foreign minister April 15 from trade representative 
Mickey Kantor at a global trade meeting in Marrakech, Morocco. 
The United States and Japan have "fundamentally different 
interpretations" of the framework objectives, a senior MITI 
official said last week, adding Japan will respond to the U.S. 
proposal after next week's string of national holidays. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

