<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Reaction to Hata's Election Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Reaction to Hata's Election Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kono Criticizes Delay in Choice </H4>

<F P=102> OW2504041194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0344 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504041194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- A top opposition lawmaker 
criticized the ruling coalition on Monday for the lengthy 
wrangling among its members over key policy issues that caused a 
delay in selecting the new prime minister. Yohei Kono, 
president of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), said, "it took 
a long time since Prime Minister (Morhihiro) Hosokawa announced 
his intention to resign." 
  "That created concerns and caused troubles for the people." 
  The seven-party coalition agreed on key policy issues last 
Friday and decided to select Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata as 
its candidate to succeed Hosokawa, two weeks after Hosokawa said 
he would step down because of a Diet stalemate over his 
financial impropriety. 
  Hata will be elected new prime minister Monday afternoon. 
  "The coalition should have a serious soul-searching over the 
political vacuum," Kono told reporters. 
  The LDP chief also blasted the Hosokawa administration, 
which 
came to power with a vow to clean up politics, for its failure 
to restore the credibility of the Japanese politics. "The 
people's distrust in politics deepened instead," he said. 
  "Mr. Hosokawa was himself not so enthusiastic about 
clarifying the suspicions" over his past financial deals "and 
the coalition members clammed up on the issue," Kono said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-6852 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas079_a_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Reaction to Hata's Election Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Reaction to Hata's Election Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kono: Step Up Reform Efforts </H4>

<F P=102> OW2504075294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0745 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504075294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- A top opposition lawmaker 
Monday called on just-elected Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata to 
step up efforts for political reform to restore the credibility 
of Japanese politics. 
  "I want to see him work toward dispelling the people's 
distrust in politics," said Yohei Kono, president of the Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP). "I heard the ruling coalition say 
repeatedly that it should follow through on promised political 
reform in order to restore the credibility of politics," Kono 
told reporters. 
  Earlier in the day, Hata was elected prime minister to 
succeed Morihiro Hosokawa, who announced his resignation on 
April 8 over financial improprieties. 
  The LDP chief said his party may or may not cooperate with 
the coalition, depending on whether the new administration will 
do things for the benefit of the people. "If they carry out 
steps that bring profits to the people, we will cooperate, but 
if they take a stance that is not beneficial for the people, we 
should stand firmly against them," he said. 
  Kono also said at a meeting of LDP legislators that his 
party 
should take a firm stance against the coalition's "forcible" 
handling of Diet business. "The coalition's forcible way in its 
handling of Diet business could destroy Japan's democracy...we 
should firmly oppose that," he said. 
  Kono earlier criticized the coalition for a delay in 
selecting Hata as their candidate for premier. "It took too 
long since Hosokawa announced his intention to resign," Kono 
said. 
  "The coalition should do some serious soul searching for the 
political vacuum," he said. 
  On the LDP's intraparty affairs, Kono said he had agreed 
with 
former Foreign Minister Michio Watanabe over joint efforts for 
party reform. During the political uncertainty following 
Hosokawa's resignation announcemment Watanabe expressed his 
intention to leave the party to become a candidate for the 
premiership, but later dropped the plan after he failed to 
secure enough support among the coalition members or among his 
followers for the move. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-6853 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas079_a_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-079 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Reaction to Hata's Election Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Reaction to Hata's Election Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Kumano on Hata's Trade Policy </H4>

<F P=102> OW2504064394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0636 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504064394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- Japan's new government 
under Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata will uphold the trade policy 
of his predecessor, Morihiro Hosokawa, a senior trade ministry 
official said Monday. The basic framework of the ruling 
coalition will be the same under the Hata government, to be 
inaugurated later Monday, Hideaki Kumano, vice international 
trade and industry minister, told a press conference. 
  The Ministry of International Trade and Industry (MITI) will 
focus "in earnest" on implementing macroeconomic steps and 
deregulation in line with goals Japan set in the 15.25 trillion 
yen stimulus package released in February and in a 
market-opening package adopted last month, Kumano said. 
  MITI will make particular efforts to deregulate 
distribution, 
information and telecommunications as well as land policy. 
  On trade issues with the United States, he said Tokyo will 
continue to seek an early reopening of the stalled trade 
"framework" talks through more dialogue. 
  Washington has repeatedly said since February's collapse of 
the framework talks that "the door is still open," while Japan 
has stressed the need for "more efforts at communication," 
Kumano said. 
  On reported new U.S. framework proposals made at an April 15 
meeting between Hata as foreign minister and trade 
representative Mickey Kantor in Marrakech, Morocco, Kumano said 
both parties agreed to keep the content of the talks secret. 
  Kumano denied reports that MITI will send a ranking official 
to Washington after the holiday season next week to respond to 
the reported U.S. proposals. "Nothing has been decided on the 
issue," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

