<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reportage on Reaction to Hata's Election Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reportage on Reaction to Hata's Election Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Business Community Welcomes Election </H4>

<F P=102> OW2504125894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1241 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504125894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- The business community 
welcomed the election Monday [25 April] of Foreign Minister 
Tsutomu Hata as Japan's new prime minister. 
  Shoichiro Toyoda, chairman of Japan's top automaker Toyota 
Motor Corp., said he expects Hata, with deep perspectives and 
rich experience in administration, to demonstrate his leadership. 
  Yasuo Shingu, chairman of Sumitomo Metal Industries Ltd., 
expressed hope that the Hata government will take quick action 
in dealing with pending problems. 
  Reiichi Yumikura, chairman of the Japan Chemical Fibers 
Association, urged the government to carry the fiscal 1994 
budget through the Diet as soon as possible in view of the slow 
recovery in the domestic economy. 
  Masaru Hayami, head of the Japan Association of Corporate 
Executives (Keizai Doyukai), said the government should try to 
cut expenditures and abolish or amend the consumption tax to 
create new sources for public welfare funds. 
  Yutaka Kume, chairman of the Japan Automobile Manufacturers 
Association, expressed hope that the government will pave the 
way for a smooth settlement of external trade problems ahead of 
a summit of the Group of Seven nations to be held in Naples, 
Italy this July. 
  Katsuhiro Utada, vice chairman of the powerful Federation of 
Economic Organizations (Keidanren), described Hata as the right 
person to tackle the major domestic and international issues 
facing Japan. 
  Utada cited the issues as an early enactment of the 1994 
state budget pending before the Diet and resumption of 
negotiations for a new trade framework between Japan and the 
United States. 
  Utada, honorary chairman of Ajinomoto Co., said the urgent 
task facing the ruling coalition is to stabilize the political 
situation and Hata is the most suitable person for the mission. 

</TEXT>

