<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Joint Parliament Group Formed by 130 Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Joint Parliament Group Formed by 130 Members </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504120094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1135 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 25 KYODO -- A 130-member joint 
parliamentary group was formed in the House of Representatives 
on Monday [25 April] to support newly elected Prime Minister 
Tsutomu Hata. The group, called "Kaishin" (Renovation), 
comprises Hata's 62-member Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], the 
37-member Japan New Party (JNP) led by Hata's predecessor as 
premier Morihiro Hosokawa, the 19-member Democratic Socialist 
Party (DSP), the seven-member Liberal Party and the four-member 
Kaikaku no Kai, party officials said. 
  Toshio Yamaguchi, an independent member, also joined the 
bloc. 
  The Liberal Party led by Koji Kakizawa and Kaikaku no Kai 
led 
by Takeo Nishioka were formed by defectors from the opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP). 
  New Party Mirai (Future), another five-member LDP breakaway, 
did not join "Kaishin" but plans to take part in the future, a 
senior Shinseito official said. 
  DSP Chairman Keigo Ouchi urged the formation of a new joint 
alliance, saying, "we should create a strongly united grouping 
to support new Prime Minister Hata." Ouchi made the call in a 
meeting of DSP legislators. 
  However, new party Sakigake [Harbinger] head Masayoshi 
Takemura, the chief cabinet secretary in the Hosokawa cabinet, 
rejected the scheme. 
  Sakigake, poised to distance itself from the dominant 
Shinseito-Komeito alliance in the coalition, has pledged not to 
take a post in the new government but voted for Hata in the 
prime ministerial vote in the Diet. 
  Tomiichi Murayama, chairman of the 74-member Social 
Democratic Party (SDP), expressed displeasure with the move 
toward a joint alliance, saying, "I cannot say it is good or 
bad. But also I cannot say `please do as you like'." 
  DSP sources said Ouchi and Shinseito Secretary General 
Ichiro 
Ozawa, the chief strategist in the coalition, met secretly at 
the end of last week and agreed on the formation of a new joint 
parliamentary group. 
  Hosokawa called for the creation of a joint parliamentary 
group, called "Kaikaku" (Reform), with other coalition parties 
in the lower house on April 8 when he announced his sudden 
resignation. 
  The idea had been frozen because of criticism from Sakigake 
[Harbinger] and the SDP, which charged that such a proposal 
would lead to the formation of a large new party amalgamating 
the JNP, Shinseito and Komeito. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

