<H3> <TI>   Outgoing Auto Official Notes Progress With U.S. </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Outgoing Auto Official Notes Progress With U.S. </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2304141894 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 22 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 8--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2304141894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Yutaka Kume, chairman of the Japan Automobile 
Manufacturers' Association, who will step down from his post in 
May, looked back at his term of office during which he was quite 
busy in dealing with economic frictions between Japan and the 
United States. On the Big Three, he said: "We can welcome the 
fact that they are beginning to respond to our demand that `they 
should make cars which suit the Japanese market.'" In this way, 
he positively assessed the changes in the stand of the Big 
Three, who have begun to produce cars with a steering wheel on 
the right-hand side. 

</TEXT>

