<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Trade Talks Expected To Resume in May </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. Trade Talks Expected To Resume in May </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2304031094 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 23 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2304031094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 23 April Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] With regard to the issue of resuming the 
Japanese-U.S. economic framework talks, a senior official with 
the Ministry of International Trade and Industry [MITI] said on 
22 April, "Japan and the United States will hold informal 
consultations to discuss resuming the stalled framework talks 
after the May holidays." The MITI senior official expressed an 
eagerness for a resumption of the stalled framework talks, 
saying: "During the consultations, Japan and the United States 
will discuss not only such macroeconomic measures as continued 
tax cuts and an increase in public investment, but also the 
adoption of objective criteria to measure the openness of the 
Japanese market and individual sectors. Japan seeks to reach a 
set of agreements with the United States in the framework talks 
prior to the industrialized nations' summit (the Naples summit) 
scheduled for July." 
  The senior MITI official indicated that vice-ministerial 
officials from the two countries will hold the informal 
consultations, adding that "the two countries need to hold 
several rounds of informal consultations before the summit talks 
are held." The MITI official went on to say: "In order for the 
stalled framework talks to be resumed an early date and for the 
two countries to reach a set of agreements, the macroeconomic 
measures are important, but Japan should not defer the 
discussion of individual sectors at the framework talks. The 
two countries need to reach a set of agreements on both 
macroeconomic and microeconomic measures prior to the summit 
talks." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

