Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Hints at Unilateral Sanctions on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Hints at Unilateral Sanctions on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2304064794 Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN in Japanese 22 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2304064794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo TOKYO SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In connection with the issue of North Korea's 
suspected development of nuclear weapons, a top Foreign Ministry 
official on 21 April touched on the possibility of Japan 
imposing its own economic sanctions against North Korea before 
the UN Security Council votes to impose them on that country. 
He then said, "Japan has been consulting with the United States 
about various options." In this way, the top Foreign Ministry 
official hinted at the possibility of both Japan and the United 
States imposing their own economic sanctions on North Korea 
before the UN Security Council decides to impose them on that 
country. 
  Both Japan and the United States are believed to have been 
studying the possibility of imposing their own economic 
sanctions on North Korea before the UN Security Council decides 
to do so in anticipation that China's opposition to the 
sanctions may block the UN Security Council from voting to 
impose the economic sanctions, thereby delaying enforcement of 
the economic sanctions against the DPRK. 
  Tsutomu Hata, deputy prime minister and foreign minister, 
and 
U.S. Defense Secretary Perry are scheduled to meet on the 
morning of 22 April and are likely to discuss this possibility 
during their meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

