<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   NPSC Official on Preparations for Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    NPSC Official on Preparations for Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2404070494 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 23 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2404070494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kanju Sato, chairman of the National Public Safety 
Commission [NPSC] (and concurrently minister of home affairs), 
was present at a news conference held after the 22 April cabinet 
meeting. Touching on measures to be taken if the UN Security 
Council imposes sanctions on the DPRK (North Korea) in 
connection with its suspected nuclear weapons development 
program, Chairman Sato stated, "In my position as NPSC chairman, 
I have requested various agencies with the National Police 
Agency [NPA] playing the leading role to compile a manual, as 
well as to come up with carefully planned measures to prepare 
for unforeseen contingencies." In this way, he disclosed that 
measures for ensuring public safety are under study now. 
Maintaining that "(details of the measures) should not be 
disclosed in concrete terms," Chairman Sato avoided mentioning 
concrete details. However, he stressed that "these measures 
will be taken within the framework of existing laws." He then 
added, "Maximum diplomatic efforts should be made to avoid 
sanctions." 
  In connection with this issue, the NPSC Information Office 
issued the following comments on the morning of the same day: 
"This means that the NPA is currently reviewing and studying 
points at issue in connection with various situations, but it 
does not mean that a practical manual is being prepared now." 

</TEXT>

