<H3> <TI>   Defense Official Notes Legal Curbs on Action </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Defense Official Notes Legal Curbs on Action </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2404021294 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 22 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2404021294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [The following item did not appear in the 22 April Morning </F>
Edition of MAINICHI SHIMBUN] 
  [Text] Because of the situation on the Korean peninsula, 
Ichiro Ozawa, Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] secretary general, 
and other lawmakers are talking about "emergency defense 
legislation" at the ruling parties' policy meeting. In this 
regard, Shigeru Hatakeyama, administrative vice minister of the 
Defense Agency [DA], said at a news conference on 20 April that 
"The emergency defense legislation that Mr. Ozawa is talking 
about is different from the general emergency legislation that 
we studied before in terms of its characteristics and range of 
influence." He explained his opinion that Ozawa's "emergency 
defense legislation" is not general legislation but rather a 
concept designed to deal with the DPRK's suspected nuclear 
weapons development program. 
  Hatakeyama first said that "the general emergency 
legislation 
deals with various peacetime regulations regarding movements of 
the Self-Defense Forces [SDF] during emergencies." He then 
explained his view, saying, "I think that lawmakers, when they 
talk about the emergency defense legislation, must keep in mind 
the cooperation that Japan can give to the international 
community, as well as the support that Japan can provide to the 
U.S. military, when the UN Security Council adopts a resolution 
to deal with an emergency situation on the Korean peninsula." 
  As for "collective security," Hatakeyama said that "the DA 
does not have a particular definition concerning actions for 
collective security." However, on the question of whether the 
SDF can cooperate with the international community in the area 
of logistics to deal with an emergency on the Korean peninsula 
within the scope of the current laws, Hatakeyama explained his 
understanding that "there are many things we cannot do unless we 
give power to the SDF by revising the current laws or by 
introducing new laws." 

</TEXT>

