<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Comments on National Welfare Tax </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hosokawa Comments on National Welfare Tax </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2304123594 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 21 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2304123594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa held a meeting 
over dinner with Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura and 
Deputy Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Hatoyama at a restaurant in 
Tokyo on 20 April. Commenting on the concept of the "national 
welfare tax," which he proposed last February and later 
retracted, the prime minister revealed that despite his own 
intentions, the bureaucracy, including the Finance Ministry, had 
exerted stronger influence. For example, he said: "I tried to 
take advantage of the Finance Ministry and other government 
agencies to achieve my goals. However, it turned out that I was 
the one who was exploited by the bureaucrats. I was swayed by 
what they said." 
  In connection with the news conference on the announcement 
of 
the national welfare tax being held in the early hours of 3 
February, Takemura said: "I ran all over the place to try to 
stop the news conference." In response, Hosokawa reportedly 
indicated he "learned his lesson," saying: "I should have not 
held the news conference at all. I should have postponed it 
until the next day. It was unreasonable." 
  That night, however, when rumors of Hosokawa's remarks 
spread 
through Nagato-cho [the district in Tokyo where the Diet 
building is located], the prime minister telephoned Takemura and 
asked him "not to disclose the details." Thus, the relations 
between the prime minister and the chief cabinet secretary 
remained awkward until the very end. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

