<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Full-Scale' U.S.-DPRK Contact Resumes </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Full-Scale' U.S.-DPRK Contact Resumes </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2404010894 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0000 GMT 24 
April 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK2404010894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The United States and North Korea have resumed a 
full-scale contact and have begun to iron out their differences 
of opinion. 
  In a response to a message sent by Kang Sok-chu, North 
Korean 
vice foreign minister and chief of North Korean delegates to 
U.S.-North Korean talks on 19 April, it was learned in the 
United States that U.S. delegation head Galluci delivered a 
reply to the North side last week. 
  The two sides exchanged basic proposals regarding the mutual 
practice of additional inspections and high-level U.S.-North 
Korean talks. It was learned that the two sides will begin 
full-scale working negotiations to reach an agreement on these 
items within this week. 
  A well-informed source on the nuclear issue said that North 
Korea withdrew its previous stance stating it has kept all the 
agreements reached with the United States by disclosing that it 
was compelled to break the agreement last month because of a 
precondition that the special envoys of the North and South 
should be exchanged. The source said that this hints at a 
positive change in the North Korean stance. 
  It was also learned that the United States, through 
Gallucci's reply, informed the DPRK of its stance over the 
suspension of Team Spirit and high-level U.S.-North Korean talks. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

