<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Fujii Talks With U.S. Treasury Secretary </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Fujii Talks With U.S. Treasury Secretary </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2404153694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1526 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2404153694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 24 KYODO -- Japanese Finance 
Minister Hirohisa Fujii tried again Sunday to convince his U.S. 
counterpart about Japan's measures to lift the economy. 
  Fujii said he told U.S. Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen 
that 
the record 15.25 trillion yen stimulus package adopted in 
February is proceeding "steadily" and "the economy is gradually 
showing brightness." He was speaking to reporters after 
emerging from a 30-minute talk with Bentsen at the Treasury 
Department ahead of a meeting of finance ministers and central 
bankers from the Group of Seven (G-7) industrialized nations in 
the afternoon. 
  Fujii said he also explained that a policy accord newly 
reached by the coalition parties endorsed the direction for 
"comprehensive" tax reform to be decided in June and enacted by 
the end of the year. 
  He did not say whether he told Bentsen about the scale and 
other details in continuing the 5.47 trillion yen cut in income 
and residential taxes included in the February package for only 
fiscal 1994 that started April 1. 
  Bentsen was unavailable for comment on the talks. But he 
previously said the single-year tax plan is not enough for Japan 
to boost domestic demand and reduce trade surplus, and has 
called on Japan to take further fiscal measures. 
  Fujii said he heard no particular requests from Bentsen on 
the matter during the talks. 
  While citing improvements in the economy, Fujii said he also 
told Bentsen that Japanese economy is "not as weak as" the 
projections released last week by the International Monetary 
Fund (IMF). 
  The IMF said in its twice-yearly world economic outlook that 
Japan's economic growth in terms of real gross domestic product 
(GDP) is expected at 0.7 percent in 1994. 
  The Japanese Government is projecting a 2.4 percent growth 
for fiscal 1994. 
  Fujii declined to comment on currency exchange rates, saying 
the two financial leaders agreed not to make any public comment. 
When pressed later by reporters whether exchange rates were 
raised at the meeting, a Japanese official said only Fujii made 
an overall presentation of the Japanese economy "from various 
points." 
  Japanese officials briefing reporters said Fujii spent most 
of the 30-minute session with Bentsen trying to explain the 
current condition of the Japanese economy. 
  They said Fujii assured Bentsen that the new cabinet to be 
formed under Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata will continue to keep 
policy unchanged toward deregulating the Japanese economy and 
carrying out economic reform. 
  Regarding the stalled trade talks with the United States, 
Japanese officials said Fujii emphasized the importance of 
Japan-U.S. relations in suggesting Japan's desire to resume the 
so-called "framework" talks as soon as possible. 
  Fujii also explained that Japan's trade surplus has started 
to decline, noting the Japanese current account surplus shrank 
in yen terms last year, the officials said. 
  Japanese officials said Fujii also pledged Japan's 
cooperation with the U.S. in extending aid to Russia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-6896 </DOCNO>
